      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, my tomato plants are acting weird. the leaves on the bottom of the stems are turning this sickly yellow color but the top ones look okay. what's probably going on and how do i fix the soil?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The yellowing leaves on the bottom of your tomato plant stems are likely due to a lack of light, which can cause the lower leaves to become scorched and turn yellow. This is a common issue, especially if your plants are top-heavy with fruit or if they're not receiving enough direct sunlight. You can try pruning the lower leaves to improve air circulation and reduce moisture, which can help prevent fungal diseases that thrive in damp environments. \n\nAs for the soil, it's probably just a matter of adjusting the pH levels. Tomatoes prefer a slightly acidic to neutral soil pH, between 6.0 and 7.0. You can test your soil pH with a DIY kit or send a sample to a lab for analysis. If your soil is too alkaline, you can add elemental sulfur or peat moss to lower the pH. \n\nIt's also worth noting that some tomato varieties are more prone to this issue than others. If you're growing a variety like 'Brandywine' or 'Cherokee Purple', you might need to provide more support to prevent the lower leaves from becoming scorched. \n\nBy the way, have you considered using a trellis or cage to support your tomato plants? This can help improve air circulation",
      "source": "target",
